[[File:080515 Nakayama Otsuka aerial.jpg|thumb|200px|right|{{center|Nakayama Otsuka Kofun, 2008}}{{Small|{{ill|GSI Aerial Photography|ja|国土航空写真}}.}}]]
'''Nakayama Otsuka Kofun''' (中山大塚古墳) is a keyhole-shaped {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳}} from the early Kofun period located in Nakayama Town, Tenri City, Nara Prefecture, Japan. It belongs to the {{ill|Kayo Kofun Cluster|ja|萱生古墳群}}, a branch of the {{ill|Ōyamato Kofun Group|ja|大和古墳群}}, and is designated as a National Historic Site as part of the Yamato Kofun Cluster.

== Overview ==

The tumulus is oriented with the rectangular front portion facing southwest and measures approximately 130 meters in total length. The rear circular portion has a diameter of about 67 meters and a height of 11.3 meters, constructed in three tiers. A fan-shaped protrusion was identified on the northern side of the rear mound, suggesting a connection to the distinctive shape of nearby {{ill|Kushiyama Kofun|ja|櫛山古墳}} in the {{ill|Yanagimoto Kofun Cluster|ja|柳本古墳群}}. Additionally, a triangular protrusion is present on the eastern side of the front mound.

The construction techniques reflect characteristics of the earliest keyhole-shaped tumuli, including a lower height for the front portion and gently curved front lines. Fragments of {{ill|special pedestals and jars|ja|特殊器台・特殊壺}} were discovered near the rear mound protrusion, linking the kofun to the oldest examples of keyhole-shaped tumuli such as {{ill|Hashihaka Kofun|ja|箸墓古墳}}.

== Construction ==

The mound's soil was sourced by cutting the southern ridge, which was shaped into the rear mound, while the front portion was carved to refine its form. Over four meters of the rear mound's height consists of artificial fill, layered with alternating clay and gravel for stability.

== Burial Facility ==

Excavations conducted since 1977 revealed a 7.5-meter-long vertical stone chamber at the center of the rear mound. The chamber's stones were sourced from the base of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山 (奈良県・大阪府)}} and exhibit intricate construction techniques such as inward-sloping upper walls. A {{ill|split-bamboo-shaped wooden coffin|ja|割竹形木棺}} was confirmed within the chamber.

== Surrounding Features ==

The lowest tier of the mound features a flat terrace about 6 meters wide and 1 meter high, with traces of a moat observed along the northwest of the rear mound and the constricted middle section. The kofun is located within the precincts of {{ill|Ōyamato Shrine|ja|大和神社}}, with a section of the southern front mound repurposed for the shrine's outer site, housing the Mitamaya Shrine (Ōyamato Wakamiya).

== Historical Significance ==

In 2014, Nakayama Otsuka Kofun was designated a National Historic Site as part of the "Yamato Kofun Cluster," alongside {{ill|Nomugi Kofun|ja|ノムギ古墳}} and {{ill|Shimoikeyama Kofun|ja|下池山古墳}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/40100003861|title=Yamato Kofun Cluster|publisher=Cultural Heritage Online|accessdate=2021}}</ref>

<gallery>
File:中山大塚古墳 出土品.JPG|Excavated items<br />{{Small|Photographed during a special exhibition at the Nara Historical and Cultural Village.}}
</gallery>

