[[File:080515 Nakayama Otsuka aerial.jpg|thumb|200px|right|{{center|Nakayama Otsuka Kofun, 2008}}
{{Small|{{ill|GSI Aerial Photography|ja|国土航空写真|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/GSI Aerial Photography|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.}}]]
'''Nakayama Otsuka Kofun''' (中山大塚古墳) is a keyhole-shaped [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]] from the early Kofun period located in Nakayama Town, Tenri City, Nara Prefecture, Japan. It belongs to the {{ill|Kayo Kofun Cluster|ja|萱生古墳群|lt=Kayō Kofun Group|1=Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kayo Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 大和古墳群}}, a branch of the {{ill|Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|ja|大和古墳群|1=Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōyamato Kofun Cluster|qq=}}, and is Historic Site1 as a National Historic Site as part of the Yamato Kofun Cluster.

== Overview ==

The tumulus is oriented with the rectangular front portion facing southwest and measures approximately 130 meters in total length. The rear circular portion has a diameter of about 67 meters and a height of 11.3 meters, constructed in three tiers. A fan-shaped protrusion was identified on the northern side of the rear mound, suggesting a connection to the distinctive type of nearby [[:en:Kushiyama Kofun|Kushiyama Kofun]] in the {{ill|Yanagimoto Kofun Cluster|ja|柳本古墳群|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yanagimoto Kofun Cluster|qq=}}. Additionally, a triangular protrusion is present on the eastern side of the front mound.

The construction techniques reflect characteristics of the earliest keyhole-shaped tumuli, including a lower height for the front portion and gently curved front lines. Fragments of {{ill|special pedestals and jars|ja|特殊器台・特殊壺|1=Special platforms and jars|1=Special platforms and jars|lt=Special plattypes and jars|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/special pedestals and jars|13=User:Immanuelle/Special platforms and jars|qq=}} were discovered near the rear mound protrusion, linking the kofun to the oldest examples of keyhole-shaped tumuli such as [[:en:Hashihaka Kofun|Hashihaka Kofun]].

== built ==

The mound's soil was sourced by cutting the southern ridge, which was shaped into the rear mound, while the front portion was carved to refine its type. Over four meters of the rear mound's height consists of artificial fill, layered with alternating clay and gravel for stability.

== burial ==

Excavations conducted since 1977 revealed a 7.5-meter-long vertical stone chamber at the center of the rear mound. The chamber's stones were sourced from the base of [[:en:Mount Nijō|Mount Nijō]] and exhibit intricate construction techniques such as inward-sloping upper walls. A {{ill|split-bamboo-shaped wooden coffin|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/split-bamboo-shaped wooden coffin|13=User:Immanuelle/Waritakegata Mokkan|qq=}} was confirmed within the chamber.

== Surrounding Features ==

The lowest tier of the mound features a flat terrace about 6 meters wide and 1 meter high, with traces of a moat observed along the northwest of the rear mound and the constricted middle section. The kofun is located within the precincts of [[:en:Ōyamato Shrine|Ōyamato Shrine]], with a section of the southern front mound repurposed for the shrine's outer site, housing the Mitamaya Shrine (Ōyamato Wakamiya).

== Historical Significance ==

In 2014, Nakayama Otsuka Kofun was Historic Site1 a National Historic Site as part of the "Yamato Kofun Cluster," alongside {{ill|Nomugi Kofun|ja|ノムギ古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nomugi Kofun|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} and {{ill|Shimoikeyama Kofun|ja|下池山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimoikeyama Kofun|qq=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/40100003861|title=Yamato Kofun Cluster|publisher=Historic Site Online|accessdate=2021}}</ref>

